1
00:00:00,050 --> 00:00:06,708
Day 4, a 7-cent mismatch led me to a bug that was quietly eating 5 times my fees.

2
00:00:06,708 --> 00:00:08,125
I can't code.

3
00:00:08,125 --> 00:00:10,263
AI trades my thousand.

4
00:00:10,263 --> 00:00:11,416
Day 4.

5
00:00:11,416 --> 00:00:17,277
End of day reconcile — bot's internal accounting said one thing, Coinbase said another.

6
00:00:17,277 --> 00:00:19,097
7 cents apart.

7
00:00:19,097 --> 00:00:20,166
Honestly?

8
00:00:20,166 --> 00:00:21,916
I almost let it go.

9
00:00:21,916 --> 00:00:23,472
Seven cents.

10
00:00:23,472 --> 00:00:24,791
Who cares.

11
00:00:24,791 --> 00:00:26,361
I checked anyway.

12
00:00:26,361 --> 00:00:29,791
And found — the fee formula was wrong.

13
00:00:29,791 --> 00:00:32,388
Supposed to be notional times rate.

14
00:00:32,388 --> 00:00:34,972
I'd written margin times rate.

15
00:00:34,972 --> 00:00:37,833
Underreporting fees by 5x.

16
00:00:37,833 --> 00:00:39,708
Every single trade.

17
00:00:39,708 --> 00:00:42,611
One trade — you'd never notice.

18
00:00:42,611 --> 00:00:45,569
A thousand trades — different business.

19
00:00:45,569 --> 00:00:47,611
You know the worst kind of bug?

20
00:00:47,611 --> 00:00:50,194
Not the one that crashes your program.

21
00:00:50,194 --> 00:00:51,902
That one gets fixed.

22
00:00:51,902 --> 00:00:56,527
The worst one is the bug that lets you feel like you're winning on your way to losing.

23
00:00:56,527 --> 00:01:00,097
Most people don't go broke from one big mistake.

24
00:01:00,097 --> 00:01:07,958
They go broke from a thousand quiet defaults that compound into a surprise that wasn't a surprise to anyone paying attention.

25
00:01:07,958 --> 00:01:13,833
Day 5 tomorrow — an agent I built posted a message I never asked for.

26
00:01:13,833 --> 00:01:15,277
Follow along.

